ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis of PCDs-PK nanohybrids is schematically illustrated in Scheme 1a
                        , with detailed procedures provided in the materials and methods section. In this design, carbon dots (CDs) were prepared as nanophotosensitizers according to our previous report [38]. PCDs were intended for targeted and highly efficient sterilization. PK was incorporated as a “glue” to combine these functional PCDs through hydrogen bonding and π–π stacking interactions, while also aiding in biofilm elimination. The successful preparation of PCDs-PK nanohybrids was initially verified by transmission electron microscopy (TEM). As shown in Figures S1 and 1a, both CDs and PCDs appeared as well-dispersed quasi-spherical particles with mean diameters of 2.27 and 2.67 nm, respectively. High-resolution TEM (HR-TEM) images revealed the same lattice fringes of around 0.21 nm for both types, indicating the presence of graphite-like structures. To further investigate the crystal structure of CDs and PCDs, X-ray diffraction analysis was performed. As shown in Figure S2, both CDs and PCDs display a broad diffraction peak centered at 25°, corresponding to the disordered arrangement of carbon atoms resulting from successful carbonization. The relatively broad nature of the peak can be attributed to their small particle size. As anticipated, the average diameter of PCDs-PK nanohybrids, composed of PCDs and PK, increased to 51.94 nm (Fig. 1b
                        ). As a versatile nanohybrids designed for biofilm degradation and targeted aPDT, the biofilm-responsive release of PCDs was also evaluated. As shown in Fig. 1c and Figure S3, homogeneous discrete PCDs were observed in PCDs-PK nanohybrids after incubation with mature biofilms or treatment with keratin (specific degrading PK). These results demonstrate that PCDs-PK nanohybrids effectively composite and specifically dissociate as designed. Subsequently, Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR), X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) and Zeta potential measurements were conducted to investigate the surface conditions and chemical composition of the materials and to further confirm the fabrication of PCDs-PK nanohybrids. As depicted in Fig. 1d, CDs displayed prominent peaks at 1385 and 1660 cm−1, and a broad peak between 3200 and 3500 cm−1, corresponding to C − N, C = O, and OH/NH stretching vibrations, respectively. These peaks suggest the presence of amino, hydroxyl groups, and N/O-containing heterocycles on the surface of the CDs. The abundant amino groups provide active sites for subsequent PBA modification. Compared with CDs, the FT-IR spectrum of PCDs showed a significantly increased peak at about 1100 cm−1, assigned to the stretching vibration of the aromatic ring, and a decreased peak at around 3200 cm−1, attributed to the NH stretching vibration of amino groups, indicating the effective conjugation of PBA via an amide bonding reaction. The FT-IR spectrum of PCDs-PK nanohybrids showed similar characteristic peaks to those of PCDs, with the exception of a reduced stretching vibration peak of the aromatic ring. The FT-IR results provide reliable evidence supporting the high water solubility of CDs and PCDs. As shown in Figure S4, both CDs and PCDs maintained good dispersion in aqueous solutions without significant aggregation, even after one month at a concentration of 10 mg mL−1, addressing the dispersion issues and ACQ commonly associated with traditional photosensitizers. According to the XPS analysis results provide in Figures S5 and S6, the XPS spectra of both CDs and PCDs exhibit characteristic peaks for C (284.9 eV), O (531.9 eV), N (399.9 eV), and S (162.9 eV). High-resolution (HR) XPS spectra of C 1 s, N 1 s, O 1 s, and S 2p further confirm the presence of chemical bonds, such as C = O, CO/CO-C, NC = O, CN = C, and thiolate groups, which align well with the FT-IR results. Notably, a characteristic peak for B (191.0 eV) is observed exclusively in the XPS spectrum of PCDs. The B 1 s spectrum reveals a fitting peak at 191.1 eV, attributed to the B-O bond, also indicating the successful conjugation of PBA. The Zeta potential of CDs shifted positively from −16.8 to −10.5 mV after the coupling of PBA and then shifted negatively to −14.7 mV due to the hybridization with PK (Fig. 1e). Subsequently, the optical properties, including UV–Vis absorption and FL emission, were studied. As depicted in Fig. 1f, typical absorption peaks of PCDs at around 430 and 640 nm were found in the spectrum of PCDs-PK nanohybrids. This confirms the well-preserved absorption properties of PCDs after hybridization and indicates the potential of PCDs-PK nanohybrids for deep red-light-mediated aPDT. Additionally, PCDs and PCDs-PK nanohybrids exhibited similar FL emission behavior (Fig. 1g and S7), with the maximum FL emission peak appearing at around 660 nm under optimal excitation at 420 nm, suggesting their feasibility as FL probes for bacterial imaging. The quantum yield (QY) of PCDs was determined to be 7.27 % (Table S1), which is lower than that of CDs. This reduction in QY can likely be attributed to the enhanced photosensitization activity of PCDs, driven by the intersystem crossing of electron to the excited triplet state. Finally, the stability of PCDs-PK nanohybrids was assessed through direct observation and TEM analysis. As shown in Figure S8, the PCDs-PK nanohybrids dispersed in saline remained clear with no visible precipitate even after standing for one week. TEM images further confirmed that there were no significant morphological changes in the PCDs-PK nanohybrids after one week of dispersion in saline compared to the freshly prepared sample. These results collectively demonstrate the excellent stability of the PCDs-PK nanohybrids.
